cor.test(completion_times$programming_experience, completion_times$python_experience, method = "spearman")

Summary statistics for the two distributions (plugin, no plugin):

summary(completion_times[completion_times$use_plugin == 1,]$completion_time)

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     211    1057    2240    2817    3714    9986

Visualize the two groups:

pdf('figures/completion_all.pdf', pointsize = 18)
plugin = completion_times[completion_times$use_plugin == 1,]$completion_time
no_plugin = completion_times[completion_times$use_plugin == 0,]$completion_time
boxplot(list(plugin = plugin,
             no_plugin = no_plugin),
        names = c(paste("plugin (", length(plugin), ")", sep = ""),
                    paste("no_plugin (", length(no_plugin), ")", sep = ""))
        )
dev.off()
## png 
##   2

The two groups are statistically indistinguishable:

t.test(completion_times[completion_times$use_plugin == 1,]$completion_time,
       completion_times[completion_times$use_plugin == 0,]$completion_time)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  completion_times[completion_times$use_plugin == 1, ]$completion_time and completion_times[completion_times$use_plugin == 0, ]$completion_time
## t = -1.0264, df = 213.46, p-value = 0.3058
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -898.5202  283.1755
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  2509.790  2817.462

Visualize the two groups separately for each task:

for (cate in sort(unique(completion_times$category))) {
  plugin = completion_times[completion_times$category == cate &
                              completion_times$use_plugin == 1,]$completion_time
  no_plugin = completion_times[completion_times$category == cate &
                                 completion_times$use_plugin == 0,]$completion_time
  pdf(paste0('figures/completion_', cate, '.pdf'), pointsize = 18)
  boxplot(list(plugin = plugin,
               no_plugin = no_plugin),
          names = c(paste("plugin (", length(plugin), ")", sep = ""),
                    paste("no_plugin (", length(no_plugin), ")", sep = "")))
  dev.off()
}

Test the two groups separately for each task:

for (cate in sort(unique(completion_times$category))) {
  plugin = completion_times[completion_times$category == cate &
                              completion_times$use_plugin == 1,]$completion_time
  no_plugin = completion_times[completion_times$category == cate &
                                 completion_times$use_plugin == 0,]$completion_time
  if (length(plugin) > 10){
    show(cate)
    show(t.test(plugin, no_plugin))
  }
}

Basic model: user and task as random effects

m_ct0 = lmer(completion_time ~
               +use_plugin
                 +
                 (1 | user)
                 +
                 (1 | task)
  , data = completion_times
  , REML = FALSE)
# vif(m_ct0)
summary(m_ct0)

Observations:

  • Using the plugin does not have a statistically significant effect on task completion time :(
  • The random effects are both very strong = there are huge differences between users and between tasks.

Add task category experience as fixed effect

m_ct1 = lmer(completion_time ~
               task_experience
                 +
                 use_plugin
                 +
                 (1 | user)
                 +
                 (1 | task)
  , data = completion_times
  , REML = FALSE)

De-mean task category experience, it may be confounded with user

m_ct2 = lmer(completion_time ~
               task_experience_between
                 +
                 task_experience_within
                 +
                 use_plugin
                 +
                 (1 | user)
                 +
                 (1 | task)
  , data = completion_times
  , control = lmerControl(optimizer = "Nelder_Mead")
  , REML = FALSE)
vif(m_ct2)

Complexity Scores - CC (Cyclomatic Complexity)

Descriptives

Number of entries in each group (plugin = 1):

table(complexity_scores$use_plugin)
## 
## FALSE  TRUE 
##   111   126

Visualize all:

boxplot(list(plugin = complexity_scores[complexity_scores$use_plugin == 1,]$cc,
             no_plugin = complexity_scores[complexity_scores$use_plugin == 0,]$cc))

The two groups are statistically indistinguishable:

t.test(complexity_scores[complexity_scores$use_plugin == 1,]$cc,
       complexity_scores[complexity_scores$use_plugin == 0,]$cc)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
##

## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.4010771  2.1123598
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  5.134921  4.279279

Visualize the two groups separately for each task:

for (category in sort(unique(complexity_scores$category))) {
  plugin = complexity_scores[complexity_scores$category == category &
                              complexity_scores$use_plugin == 1,]$cc
  no_plugin = complexity_scores[complexity_scores$category == category &
                                 complexity_scores$use_plugin == 0,]$cc
  boxplot(list(plugin = plugin,
               no_plugin = no_plugin),
          main = category,
          names = c(paste("plugin (", length(plugin), ")", sep = ""),

}

Complexity Scores - Halstead Effort

Descriptives

Visualize all:

boxplot(list(plugin = complexity_scores[complexity_scores$use_plugin == 1,]$halstead_effort,
             no_plugin = complexity_scores[complexity_scores$use_plugin == 0,]$halstead_effort))

The two groups are statistically indistinguishable:

t.test(complexity_scores[complexity_scores$use_plugin == 1,]$halstead_effort,
       complexity_scores[complexity_scores$use_plugin == 0,]$halstead_effort)

Visualize the two groups separately for each task:

for (category in sort(unique(complexity_scores$category))) {
  plugin = complexity_scores[complexity_scores$category == category &
                              complexity_scores$use_plugin == 1,]$halstead_effort
  no_plugin = complexity_scores[complexity_scores$category == category &
                                 complexity_scores$use_plugin == 0,]$halstead_effort
  boxplot(list(plugin = plugin,
               no_plugin = no_plugin),
          main = category,
          names = c(paste("plugin (", length(plugin), ")", sep = ""),
                    paste("no_plugin (", length(no_plugin), ")", sep = "")))
}

From the boxplots we see theres not much data for tasks 4, 5, and 7.

Basic model: user and task as random effects

m_ct0 = lmer(halstead_effort ~
               +use_plugin
                 +
                 (1 | user)
                 +
                 (1 | task)
  , data = complexity_scores
  , REML = FALSE)
